HEADWORD: Quaternity
<hw>Qua*ter"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>quaternitas</ets>, fr. L. <ets>quaterni</ets> four each: cf. F.
<ets>quaternit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The number
four.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The union of four in one, as of four persons; --
analogous to the theological term <xex>trinity</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Quateron</ent>⟦br⟧
